Oxfam:
Oxfam is a leading organization in emergency WaSH and Food Security in Mozambique since 1987.  Over the past five years Oxfam has implemented WaSH responses to benefit flood-affected populations in Sofala and Zambezia, cholera-affected populations in Sofala and Niassa, WaSH activities for east African refugees in Cabo Delgado and Nampula, and EFSL response for populations affected by three consecutive years of drought in Gaza.  In Mozambique Oxfam uses a single programmatic approach, linking activities in sustainable livelihoods, humanitarian assistance, good governance and gender for amore effective impact on beneficiaries.  In 2013, in coordination with COSACA members, Oxfam with its local partners implemented an emergency intervention to benefit more than 32,000 people in nine of the most flood-affected communities in Gaza and 8,000people in Zambezia province through seeds and tools fairs, food security (EFSL) and access to safe water, sanitation and hygiene promotion (WASH).  The total funding mobilized was $2 million from the Oxfam co-federation network and two bilateral donors.

The Dutch government is committed to the development and implementation of agreements between companies, social organizations, trade unions and government in the field of International Corporate Social Responsibility (IMVO) and it granted a subsidy of EUR 996.346to ensure a structured and professional involvement of civil society and trade unions in the preparation of IMVO covenants in the Netherlands. The subsidy is Intended for Dutch based established  civil society organizations involved in the IMVO Covenant negotiations. The current covenant trajectories are on: Nutrition, insurers, gold, floriculture, sustainable natural stone.
The administration of the funds is operated by Oxfam Novib on request of the MVO Platform and the Ministry.

Kukumbi is registered within the framework of laws governing civil society organizations in Mozambique under Registration No. 26 dated 3rd of April 2009. Kukumbi is a community development organization, which was founded in 1997 and recognized by the government in 1998. The founders are all residents of Zambézia Province, Mozambique. It was created in response to the demand by local people tomeet their development needs based on their experience in working with local communities during and soon after the 16-year long civil war that displaced many people. The constitution was announced in the Government Gazette III SERIES # Nr. 27 on 3rd July 2002.
Kukumbi is headed by a seven (7) member Management Committee who include a female. The Management Committee are well known in their local communities, and have extensive knowledge of the issues faced by the local people. The Management Committee, in consultation with the beneficiaries and other key stakeholders determine the policies and overall direction of the organisation and its programmes.The Management Committee has the Audit and Finance sub-committee, which monitors the management of Kukumbi resources.

The main intervention areas:
# Governance  and democracy
# Disaster risk reduction
# HIV and AIDS
# Education and Gender
# Kukumbi Institutional Development.

The Joint Humanitarian Response for Nepal Earthquake (NPJR) provides life-saving humanitarian assistance to communities affected bythe Earthquake of 25th April 2015 and ensure efficient implementation of humanitarian response activities on behalf of theDutch Relief Alliance participating members. This 6-month joint programme is implemented in the most affected districts (Nuwakot, Kathmandu, Bhaktapur, Lalitpur, Lamjung, Ghorka, Sindhupalchowk, Kavrepalanchowk) by 8 Dutch NGOs, led by Oxfam. Together they work towards three specific objectives:
1) Increase in mortality and morbidity and outbreaks of communicable diseases are prevented through immediate access to basic water, sanitation, hygiene and health services.
2) Families whose homes have been destroyed or damaged, including those displaced, attain basic, protective shelter solutions.
3) Immediate food needs of earthquake affected populations in worst affected districts are met and nutritional status of the most vulnerable populations is prevented from deteriorating.
The Joint Response will support 138,640 people in need. The total available budget for the Joint Response is Euro 4 million, funded by MoFA.

CO Mozambique - Mozambique is located in a coastal area, very vulnerable, where is cyclic on cyclones, foods, drought, cholera and other disasters. This year the affected provinces are Sofala, Manica, Tete, Zambezia, Niassa and North of Inhambane. the mostly affected province that have been devastated by Tropical Storm IDAI. is Sofala, but some districts of Zambezia are also under water. Oxfam will be responding to save lives in Zambezia and Sofala, on WASH activities and Food security.

In February 2012, the Dutch National Postcode Lottery (National Postcode loterij) approved the large and innovative Dreamfund project #Internet Now!# to be implemented in Northern Uganda. Oxfam Novib will implement the project together with 3 other project partners: Arid lands information Network (ALIN), Inveneo and Samasource.

The project is to bring services providing work and income to rural communities in Northern Uganda through reliable, affordable and sustainable high-speed connection to the Internet (providing information access through ICT). One hundred centers will be established to cover 9 districts in Northern Uganda (Gulu, Amuru, Adjumani, Moyo, Kitgum, Pader, Lamwo Nwoya and Agago). These will form a social enterprise following an innovative business model. Each center will offer solar powered workstations housed in shipping containers together with daily support and training by company staff and volunteers. The centers will be interconnected to the internet through Wi-Fi technology.

The social enterprise to be created by the project will be set up as an independent legal entity established locally in Uganda of which the initial shares will be held by the independent Dutch not for profit Stichting internet Now! SINFA which is to be established in the second quarter of 2012. One of the goals of the project is to make the company self-sustaining so its activities and contribution to the local community can continue after the initial 3 year funding for the project. . SINFA will provide income generating services in the centres, such as employment through micro work, a specialised form of business process outsourcing.  The centres also will give access to an agricultural commodity platform, and other services, all driven by specially designed information technology.

The innovative approach of the internet Now! project requires an intense level of collaboration between all parties which is expressed in the project management structure with a project management team with members of all the project partners working together in Gulu, Uganda on a daily basis. Next to that a coordination committee with members of all project partners will be established for the project all as further set out in the project initiation document.

Oxfam Novib is one of the 17 national affiliates of the Oxfam International Confederation. It started life in 1956 as the Netherlands Organisation for International Assistance (Novib), and joined forces with Oxfam in 1994.  Working together in confederation, the Oxfam affiliates can speak with one clear and compelling voice on issues of global concern: climate change, health and education forall, agriculture, trade, and conflicts and emergencies.  Oxfam established this country office to support local organizations and projects.  Through this local office Oxfam Novib directly contributes towards this projects implementation.

Oxfam Novib was founded in 1956 as the Netherlands Organisation for International Assistance (Novib), and joined forces with Oxfam in 1994.  Oxfam Novib is member of the Oxfam International confederation. Working together in the confederation, the Oxfam affiliates can speak with one clear and compelling voice on issues of global concern: climate change, health and education for all, agriculture, trade, and conflicts and emergencies.  Oxfam Novib's main office is based in The Netherlands, it supports the work of a network of local offices, the implementation of global projects, fundraising, campaigning and advocacy.  Oxfam Novibs the Hague office contributes towards this projects implementation.
